deck_excerpt: Gate Guardians combined with Branded Despia
deck_description: A sort of deck idea that has been floating around my head since Maze of Memories was introduced: Gate Guardian combined with Branded Despia. The main goal here is to work the two parts together to create a board of heavy hitters that can overwhelm your opponent. Cards like Branded Opening and Fusion Deployment can help get your combos started, being able to get certain Gate Guardian pieces in play or into the graveyard, and fetching Branded Fusion or Branded in Red. The Gate Guardian monsters (Namely Gate Guardians Combined and Gate Guardian of Wind and Water) can help protect your monsters from various targeting and spell/trap effects, while Mirrorjade can deal with monsters by banishing them or destroying them if it leaves the field. Despian Quaeritis and Gate Guardian of Water and Thunder can reduce a monster's attack points to stop them from attacking your monsters as well as help trigger Labyrinth Wall Shadow's destruction ability. There is also the possibility of using Blazing Cartesia to go into Granguignol the Dusk Dragon which in turn can get you into one of Quaeritis or even Luluwalilith. Overall the deck works a lot better than I thought it would, but it is vulnerable to being interrupted, and if a board is broken, it's not the easiest to recover.
very good deck.

deck_name: Magikey Summoned Skull Post Strong Will (MD March 2023)
deck_excerpt: One card combo ft. Rainbow Bridge of Salvation
deck_description: The game plan of this deck is pretty much the same as the one from my previous version except that now we can do it with just one card thanks to the newly released Rainbow Bridge of Salvation, which banishes itself from graveyard to add a Crystal Beast monster and any field spell from deck to hand, by adding Magikey World we can then search for both our Magikey ritual monster and Magikey ritual spell and then use the Crystal Beast monster as material for the ritual summon, all that's really needed apart from that is a card to shuffle back when searching for the ritual spell, and then actually drawing either The Monarchs Erupt or Skill Drain to stun the opponent. Anyways, the one card combo that ends on Summoned Skull is the following: Activate Foolish Burial Goods, send Rainbow Bridge of Salvation and use it's graveyard effect, add Crystal Beast Topaz Tiger and Magikey World to our hand, activate Magikey World to search for Magikey Mechmusket - Batosbuster, use World's second effect to add Magikey Maftea to our hand, activate Maftea to ritual summon Batosbuster using the level 4 Topaz Tiger, use Batosbuster effect to search for Maginificent Magikey Mafteal, activate Mafteal's effect to summon itself without using our normal summon for the turn, XYZ summon our only extra deck monster in Magikey Spirit - Vepartu using Batosbuster and Mafteal (Now we don't have extra deck cards allowing us to activate The Monarch's Erupt), activate Vepartu's effect to search for Summoned Skull and finally normal summon said Summoned Skull. Other cards that are great to add to our end board are Piercing the Darkness to make sure that Summoned Skull can win in battle and Solemn Judgment to protect our backrow from stuff like Lightning Storm. Overall this is still a cheesy and fragil one-trick pony deck meant for casual play but now it has a little more kick to it thanks to the fact that it is able to go off of one and a half cards instead of 2 and a half, so we have a bit more space for staples like Forbidden Droplet (Which is also great to send Rainbow Bridge to the grave if we are unlucky enough to draw it) and Triple Tactics Talent (I also tested Magical Mallet over this, a more F2P option if you are on a budget).
Old meta but one of my favorite decks!

deck_excerpt: They flip, they flop, and they banish non-stop
deck_description:
Karakuri took a decent hit after Halq was banned,so this is a pre-Halq ban deck that I modified into a post-Halq deck to keep the Karakuri alive. It still has a few kinks to sort out but it works pretty solidly

What you're lef with is an incredibly fun deck to play, with a number of ways to combo.

1. open with Merchant, normal summon and use his ability to search Bonze, who can then be special summoned as a tuner, Synchro summon Burei, ladder up to Bureibu using Gamas special summoned by the effects of Burei/Bureido

2. open with Anchor Drill, use effect to special summon Komachi, who will then give you a bonus normal summon, Synchro and ladder, then use the aformentioned bonus normal summon to build a second Bureido

There's a bunch more but I'll let you figure them out

Karakuri Gama Oil is a really helpful card, it can help keep combos going, or it can bring a Burei/Bureido out of the graveyard for a little extra firepower, plus the summoned monster will gain 500/500 every time a karakuri monster changes position

Karakuri is a really fun archetype, it's got a little something for every occasion. I might reccoment switching out Nibiru for a second Karakuri Klock or a Karakuri Trick Room

deck_excerpt: In short, your whole deck is pretty much hand traps some being actual trap cards that u activate from hand.
deck_description:
Okay so what we have here are the infamous Runicks collaborating with the Magical Musketeers, which share a similar mechanic of allowing their respective archtype backrow cards to activate from hand ( Runicks being their quick-spells and Musketeers being their Musket spells and traps).

The main play of this deck is thinning out your opponent's deck with Runick spells while simultaneously controlling their field with the Musketeers, and what makes it even better is that the Musketeers do not require their own cards to activate the monster effects, any spell or trap will do so you can say for example activate a Runick Tip in Magical Musketeer Caspar 's column, not only will you get another runick card from your deck, you can also activate Casper's effect to search for any Magical Musketeer card, whether monster, spell or trap card which most of the time is Magical Musket - Last Stand but it can vary depending on the context of the field. The key cards for the deck are:

Runick Fountain - The main card that makes your runick quick-spells hand traps, you will want to have this card on your field to recycle back your quick-spells and potentially draw into either more quick-spells or Musket spells and traps.

Runick Allure - Although not really necessary, It does fuel up the amount of cards you can banish for quick-spell played, and I mean any quick-play spell card so if your opponent is playing quick-plays, they will be digging their own demise.

Runick Flashing Fire / Runick Destruction / Runick Freezing Curses - Disruptions for your opponent, Flashing fire destroys a Special summoned monster, Destruction destroys a spell/trap card and Freezing curses negates a monster's effect, all Runick quick spells also can special summon their fusion monsters to the extra-monster zone for protection and adding/recovering Runick cards.

Magical Musketeer Starfire - Use her effect to special summon other Musketeers from the deck.

Magical Musketeer Caspar - Use his effect to add a Musket card to your hand, I mostly use him Turn 1 to search out Last Stand and during the next turn, you can use either a runick quick-spell or Magical musket spell or trap then add either Magical Musket - Cross-Domination or Magical Musket - Desperado for an additional disruption.

Magical Musketeer Doc  Normally use his effect late-game when you have a decent amount of Magical Musket spells and Traps in your GY to recycle them back into your hand, Oh and it can recycle any Magical Musket card, it is not only limited to the spells and traps.

Magical Musketeer Max - The catalyst for the Musketeers, given the right circumstances, upon summon you can either add up to 6 Magical Musket spells and traps ( Depending on how many monsters your opponent controls) or special summon up to 5 Magical Musketeer monsters ( Depending on how many spells and traps your opponent controls on the field) all of this from a Link-1 monster. Only downside is it conflicts a bit with the Runick fusions since they have to be summoned in the extra-monster zone, so you don't want to summon him if your hand has more Runick cards than Muskets.

Magical Musket - Cross-Domination / Magical Musket - Desperado / Magical Musket - Last Stand - The musket disruption for your opponents, Cross-Dominations negates and changes the targeted monster's attack to 0, good for getting rid of monsters when they attack, Desperado destroys any face-up card on the field. and Last Stand a counter-trap that negates spells and traps, good for negating cards like Evenly Matched or stopping Fusions/Rituals from being summoned by their spell/trap effects.

Time-Rending Morganite - It syncs pretty well with the deck strategy so why not y'know lol, draw 2 cards every draw phase to dig through your runick and musket cards faster, have 2 normal summons which go very well with the Musketeers, the only downside is monster effects can't activated from the hand but that doesn't matter because we are running spell and trap hand traps.

Hugin the Runick Wings - Searches your field spells and protects your board from getting destroyed by tributing herself which is pretty solid.

Munin the Runick Wings - Searches your Runick allure and gives you free 1000LP during the end phase, also banishes itself to negate cards that target your runick cards, which is also pretty solid.

What I like about this deck more than pure Runicks is that with the Muskets package, the two archetypes combats the other's weakpoints ( For example, Skill Drain shuts down Muskets which you can destroy with a Runick Destruction where as Chaos Hunter or Secret Village of the Spellcasters completely shuts Runicks down but can be easily outed with Magical Musket - Desperado  or Magical Musket - Cross-Domination.

The main weakness I can think of about this deck is that most of the effects 'target' your opponent's cards, so when you come across a monster that is non-targetable, well good luck getting rid of that said monster without targeting it. Maybe siding in a Dark Ruler No More or 2 might make a difference.

But then again for that price you get a recycling hand trap-system not only made of quick spells, but traps and counter traps that you can activate from your hand completely by-passing the standard set and pass to activate your traps. a spell that allows you to draw 2 cards every draw phase on top of drawing up to 3 with Runick Fountain, a Link-1 monster that can either add multiple disruption cards at once, or special summon multiple monsters.

It's honestly frustrating playing against this deck simply because you have no clue what your opponent will activate since everything that will affect your side of the field is activated from their hand, your opponent will most likely surrender out of frustration more than you decking them out.

If you have any suggestions on how it can be improved or cards that can be replaced for more consistency, let me know :)

deck_excerpt: 2023 Masterduel Agents with new Ishizu and Spright cards.
deck_description:
Possible Endboards of the Deck (from weakest to strongest): 

  1. Masterflare Hyperion; Baronne de Fleur; Spright Elf (with Diviner of the Herald in the GY)
  2. Masterflare Hyperion; Baronne De Fleur; Spright Elf (with Diviner of the Herald in the GY) + The Sanctuary in the Sky and Divine Punishment 
  3. Masterflare Hyperion; Baronne De Fleur; Spright Elf (with Diviner of the Herald in the GY) + I:P Masquerena / Herald of the Arc Light + Field Spell and Counter Trap
  4. Masterflare Hyperion; Baronne De Fleur; Spright Elf (with Diviner of the Herald in the GY) + I:P Masqerina + Herald of Arc the Light OR F.A. Dawn Dragster OR The Executor of the Underworld - Pluto + Field Spell and Counter Trap
  5. Masterflare Hyperion; Baronne De Fleur; Spright Elf (with Diviner of the Herald in the GY) + I:P Masqerina + Swordsoul Supreme Sovereign - Chengying + Field Spell and Counter Trap

Gameplan: 

The main loop is to turbo out Masterflare Hyperion and pitch a The Agent of Creation - Venus with his effect to extend towards the end board. The key is to use several Mystical Shine Ball and depending on the hand and mills there are dozens of ways to do that.

The easiest way to get to Masterflare is to summon Diviner of the Herald. Diviner pitches Trias Hierarchia to tribute itself with it and to then summon Buten (who can later turn a Shine Ball into a tuner). From there you use Protector of The Agents - Moon to search for Majesty Hyperion. From this point the combolines diverge and are heavily dependant on the hand and mills. The goal is to fuel yourself with Mystical Shine Ball to get to Celestial Knightlord Parshath, who can discard a card (ideally a Eva or one of the Millers) and search out the card you need to get to the end board: Ideally you search Divine Punishment BUT it can happen that you need to search for Neptune or even Diviner if the Fieldspell is activated to extend the combo ALSO if you milled the fieldspell you might have to either reshuffle it before you banish Neptune or you can save yourself the Parshath search / search something else. In order to get to Endboard 1 and in general all others aswell, you need to make sure to have Parshath on the field and a reachable Level/Link 2 monster to get to Spright Elf, who will serve as 1. a level 2 tuner revival to go into Baronne with Majesty and 2. interuption on opponents turn by special summoning Diviner, which can lead to a Eva activation that then gives you Herald of Orange Light.

You can get there also the themed way with The Agent of Mystery - Earth if you have either Venus or Neptune in Hand. In that case you go to your Links before you summon Masterflare. Ideally you want to get Diviner into the grave so you can revive her with Elf and get another Synchro 10.

If you have only Venus in hand you have to 1. go into the Links ending on Parshath AND a shineball (or any level/link 2) and 2. have a Diviner in the GY (mills, foolish, discard). From there its just Elf revival and the loop starts over. In this case you most likely have to pitch The Agent of Destruction - Venus to recover the shineballs. Even if you have Diviner in hand; opening with Venus can bait an Ash once you get to Moon, which might be the better way depending on your hand.

Another possible extender is to use Parshath's second effect to Special Summon a fairy from hand, when a fairy leaves the field. The main Target is obviously a Diviner, but can also be the second Majesty, Venus or Destruction Venus. However, that will require some preparations, because in order to Special Summon Diviner you need a Level 1 Fairy in Grave (Eva or Neptune). It can happen that you have to link off a Shine Ball into Link Spider, which will likely stay there for a bit and might mess with your zones a bit.

TLDR (general objectives): Get Diviner into Hand or GY, Turbo out Masterflare, Parshath search for Extender or Countertrap, Elf revives tuner to get another Synchro 10 or Diviner, Restover materials can make I:P or Herald of the Arc Light or other Extras.

Some Comments:

  1. The Main effort in this deck is to manage your monster spaces and the order of your actions. The first is important once you have to use destruction Venus to recover your shineballs and the second is simply due to there being many combolines that potentially allow you to bait many handtraps or ressources and still get to a decent endboard.
  2. With a decent hand you will generally have extra shineballs to make I:P Masquerena and the other Extras, while the minimum endboard is generally Masterflare, Elf and a synchro 10. 
  3. You will notice that the Countertrap search often has to be ditched inorder to get the extenders you need, but usually thats alright, if you can fill your hand with Orangelight or other handtraps.
  4. Considering Runick is heavily played, I tend to go for Chengying instead of Baronne, if i can end on the Counter Trap or a Herald of the Arc Light to have at least 1 omni negate.
  5. The Ishizu cards are basically there to serve as 1. Link fodder if you can special summon them 2. Tribute fodder for Trias for the card draw 3. Filling the GY with Diviner, Majesty, Trias, Eva or Neptune 4. Reshuffling your own Shine Balls to keep extending 5. Get a peak at what the opponent is playing.
  6. Once you have Neptune in Hand your mills become your second hand since you can special summon any Agent you milled.
  7. Sadly the deck bricks every now and then, which is just natural if you play 3 Garnets and the mills can go wrong if you need them to hit well, but it just happens from time to time.
  8. The interaction between Orange Light and Eva will many times give you the starter or extender you need.
  9. Handtraps: The deck can bait many Handtraps - especially with the Ishizu cards (many ash the millers and if they dont the mills can be useful) BUT it can die to an Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring or Ghost Ogre & Snow Rabbit if your hand doesn't have any follow up. Also Infinite Impermanence will become the bane of your existence UNLESS you have Trias in Hand or Grave, which entirely dodges it. Nibiru, the Primal Being can mess you up BUT with decent set-up you can play through it HOWEVER I don't really see a way to play around it unless you have Orange Light in hand.
  10. Sidedeck of this list: I think the decklist works best for now like this, but you can slot in more maxx c protection or other defensive handtraps HOWEVER i found them to be more bricky than useful overall. Having said that i think that Artifact Lancea can be a decent pick, because it is a fairy that you can pitch with Orange Light and it also shuts off Runick for a turn and can protect you from cards like Spright Smashers. I am considering slotting in an additional Green and Purple Light since Eva can search them, but I didn't test those yet. The Extra deck has a flexspot that you can fill up with what you have, I am testing Artifact Dagda right now, because it is generic which can remove a Link spider or a Nibiru token (and then serve as fodder for the Fairy links or Trias). I personally don't have Underworld Goddess of the Closed World or Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax, but both are very good I:P targets.

Just a deck I have made a while ago, if you are going to play keeper of dragon magic, I would reccomend playing it with small world + quintet magician

The Infernoble Knight support in DUNE gives the Deck a lot more consistent and powerful plays to do than the wierd Beyond the Pendulum build that is currently going around that people are coping about. Basically, access to Isolde and a Level 5 Synchro is fully combo for the Deck and the plays are pretty simple.

2 Super Quantum Red Layer, 3 Neo Space Connector, and 1 Neo-Spacian Aqua Dolphin to get to Isolde. 2 Immortal Phoenix Gearfried which is a monster negate and it is very easy to Summon. You don't need to search it as you have pretty much enough interruption in your basic combo already, but it is another addition to your end-board if you do happen to draw it. 2 Fire Flint Lady for extension. 3 Infernoble Knight - Oliver, 3 Infernoble Knight - Ogier, and 3 Infernoble Knight - Renaud. Renaud is great for extension, as a Summon off of Isolde, and he can grab back something like Living Fossil for more extension. Oliver is another extender and he can make himself into an equip which is important for this Deck. Ogier has more usage with the new Infernoble support, so having something that can foolish an equip or a FIRE Warrior is great with the new grave effects. Also, he can also make himself an equip which is important as we need at least 1 monster who can make themselves an equip in our starting combo. 1 Infernoble Knight - Ricciardetto. Drawing him is fine as he can basically make Isolde pretty easily depending on your starting hand if you do draw him, but he is also a pretty good Summon off of Isolde as well since he can reborn a FIRE Warrior on summon. 2 Infernoble Knight - Turpin which is a free summon from hand or GY if you control an equip and he can also make himself an equip.

For Spells and Traps, we are playing 3 Heritage of the Chalice and Reinforcement of the Army to search our stuff. 3 Infernoble Arms - Durendal, 2 Infernoble Arms - Almace, 1 Infernoble Arms - Joyeuse, 3 The Infernoble Arms Museum, 1 Divine Sword - Phoenix Blade, and 1 Living Fossil. Durendal searches a Level 5 or lower FIRE Warrior. Almace can equip a different Infernoble Arms from Deck. Joyeuse can add back a FIRE Warrior from GY. Noble Arms Museum searches a Noble Arms card and specials a Noble Knight that is currently an equip.

ED: 1 Baronne de Fluer, 2 Infernoble Knight Emperor Charles, 2 Infernoble Knight Captain Roland, 2 Angelica, Princess of Noble Arms, 1 Accesscode Talker, 1 Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax, 1 Knightmare Unicorn, 1 I:P Masquerena, 2 Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights, and 2 Charlemagne. Ricciardetto does Warrior lock you if you use his effect on Summon, and because you will be using that effect most of the time, you can't really play much outside of Warriors in your Extra Deck. If you aren't Warrior locked, you can make Masquerena with your extra bodies to go into Avramax or Unicorn. Angelica seraches Noble Arms Museum and if she is targeted, she can banish herself until the End Phase to foolish a FIRE Warrior from Deck and summon Captain Roland from your Extra Deck. You can target her with the effects of your Infernobles in GY that allows them to make themselves equips which then gets you to the rest of your combo. Charlemagne basically is another Charles after he equips Charles using his effect on Link Summon. Then, you can Summon your equipped Charles using Noble Arms Museum to have another body on field.

Side Deck can be whatever, but I would recommend board clearers and backrow removal for going second.

Full combo is simple: Make Isolde using whatever and dump Living Fossil to Summon out Ricciardetto. Ricciardetto revives a Level 4 non-Tuner FIRE Warrior which can be put into your GY through something like Ogier or Oliver. Synchro into Angelica and search Noble Arms Museum. Museum pay 1200 to add whatever Noble Arms you need or are missing. An Infernoble in GY targets Angelica to try to equip, and then chain Angelica to banish herself, dump Turpin, and Summon Captain Roland. Then, you can equip an Equip Spell to Roland so that you can Summon back Turpin. Synchro into Charles and equip Roland to him. Link that off into Charlemagne and effect to copy effects and equip Charles. Museum Summon out the equipped Charles. End Phase Angelica returns. If you were not Warrior locked, then you can get more bodies on field to make Masquerena, but it all depends on what you open.

This scareclaw deck was built to attempt to make negations and attack for game with tri-heart. This plays around Ash-Blossom but is susceptible to Nibiru, Sphere Mode, and sometimes Bystials. A great board that I usually want to end on is a tri-heart, Baronne, and cloudcastle (Visas Starfrost either being in hand or searched). Rescue Cat allows you to start a combo with your smaller scareclaws, but it's always nice to have at least 2 scareclaws in your starting hand. Side in the super polys if garura isn't accessible using your opponents cards (Nirbiru or Sphere Mode should be in Main). You can add in Lava Golems or Book of Eclipse/Moons to your preference.

Scareclaws >>>>>>>>>> Kashtira :)

This updated Abyss Actor deck is a going first build with decent capacity going 2nd too. The aim is have the field spell ready with a set opening ceremony going into your opponents turn, (alongside as many additional negates as possible). Once your opponent intentionally/inadvertently destroys opening ceremony, you should be able to replenish your hand traps, which will hopefully prevent them winning, so that you can counter attack on turn 3. See the video for a discussion on the build, combos from different starting hands, and discussion on alternative choices & side deck cards.

A dark world build that exchanges consistency for hilarity (and the ability to style on your opponent). Do your usual dark world plays (including hand-loops, if you can), link-climbing into Saryuja as soon as possible. Then, use it to dig for Gale Dogra, which you either normal summon or special summon off of Saryuja. Use Dogra to send Cyberdark Dragon to the GY. Keep using the Danger! brigade and darkworld extenders to dig through your deck and put both Necro Fusion and King of the Swamp into the GY, then link-climb into Knightmare Gryphon to re-set Necro Fusion. Finally, flip over Necro Fusion during your opponent's turn (banishing Cyberdark Dragon + King of the Swamp) to make Cyberdark End Dragon. 

 

Is it good? No, not at all. Is it funny to make CED during your opponent's turn? I would argue yes :D
The deck is really consistent, although, practice is really needed to perform the new combos!

deck_name: A Beginner's Guide to Branded Despia (March 2023)
deck_excerpt: Guide for those who want to learn Branded Despia post-PHHY! Youtube Link inside!
deck_description:
Branded currently is one of the top contenders for today's March 2023 meta. Able to consistently make gigantic fusion beatsticks with board clearing capabilities backed by a solid resource grindgame, Branded is currently the ultimate aggro-beatdown deck. Pushed into meta relevance by Konami because of it's fan favourite status as the "lore" deck of series 12, Branded post Photon Hypernova is a fusion powerhouse!
 
However, this Branded suffers from two major weaknesses: Ash Blossom (On esp. on Branded Fusion) and Nibiru. This version of Branded aims to fix that, by giving the pilot so much gas and plays to work with so that you can play through those devastating handtraps and eventually out-resource your opponent! This "gas" variant of Branded can keep playing, even though Branded Fusion is negated! Some hands allow the pilot to make Dragoon before you use Branded Fusion (so you can negate Ash) and before 5 summons (so you can negate Nibiru).
 
Dragoon is especially strong in today's meta vs. many meta decks since they all target/destroy, meaning this overpowered Deviantart OC is a nigh-invincible instant-win button!

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

ARCHETYPES, ENGINES AND DECKBUILDING

 
This core of this deck is composed of the traditional Branded and Despia cards. The only card that isn't standard is Dramaturge. I personally like to use Dramaturge since he can negate Mirrorjade if you're going first, which enables 2 uses of Mirrorjade's effect rather then 1 - thus getting you more dumps in the GY from the ED and more resources. 3 Tragedy is included as a banish target for Allure of Darkness (essentially a +1!).
 
The Bystial package is relatively small, since banishing Light/Dark monsters in the GY isn't very impactful and common in today's metagame. Lubellion is "searcheable" from deck since Branded Fusion dumps him to the GY,and Lubellion can summon itself from the GY by tributing the on-field Albion. Lubellion can activate from deck Branded Lost as extra protection/search power or Branded Beast for a quick effect pop during the main phase.
 
The Frightfur package is included as another piece of "gas" in the deck - maintaining hand advantage since all the pieces search each other and giving access to Polymerization (a powerful boardbreaker with Guardian Chimera).
 
Fusion Deployment functions as a toolbox in this deck, since its 3 targets each serve a distinct function. Albaz can breakboards when summoned, and Albaz + Super Poly cracks most boards nowadays. If your opponent happens to field Dragon monsters, Albaz can contact fuse them away. Cartesia enables fusion summoning as a quick effect. Not only does she give access to Granguinol (which is a foolish burial), she can protect your activating monster effects on the field from targeting negates like Impermanence and Effect Veiler. Finally, Dark Magician can be summoned from deck if you have all the pieces for Dragoon, so that you can have access to his omni-negate to deter Ash/Nibiru before you full combo.
 
50 cards are utilized in this deck rather than around 40ish since every important piece (esp. Branded Fusion) is highly searcheable anyways. 50 cards also reduces the likelihood of drawing garnets and bricks. This "gas" version of Branded is designed to draw alot, search alot, and to play alot to overwhelm any sort of interaction your opponent has whether it is Ash Blossom, Nibiru or on-board interruption.
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
 
"Gas" Branded is designed to play through your opponent's interruption to create gigantic fusion beatsticks and overwhelm with high ATK and massive resource generation. If given even a second of breathing space, your opponent will find that they are facing down a field full of powerful fusion monsters!
 
Branded Fusion is both a blessing and a curse for this strategy. The whole deck revolves around searching and resolving that card, and if it's negated, your further options are likely limited. Your obvious glaring chokepoint and weakness is Branded Fusion, so it is imperative that you can bait out the Ash Blossom or fusion summon Dragoon before you use the card. It is advisable to use every other card first like Frightfur Patchwork, Branded Opening or Lubellion so that you can bait out your opponent's Ash Blossom. Also, from experience playing the deck, I've discovered that people intentionally hold their Ash Blossom saving it for Branded Fusion - so if you don't have the card, you can bluff having it and just do all your searches/summons from deck!
 
End boards are very hand dependant, but here are the mainline combos:
 
Branded Fusion + Dark Monster + Discard = Mirrorjade (banish), Bystial Lubellion + Beast (pop), Set Branded in Red
  1. Activate Branded Fusion to summon Albion, sending Albaz + Bystial Lubellion from deck.
  2. Fusion summon Lubellion the Searing Dragon by fusing Albaz + Dark Monster with Albion. Ideal dark monsters to banish are Tragedy (search) and Dramaturge (free body on field).
  3. Lubellion (discards for cost) fusion summons Mirrorjade by shuffling back Albaz from banished pile and Lubellion the Searing Dragon on the field.
  4. Summon Bystial Lubellion from the GY by tributing Albion.
  5. Activate Lubellion's card effect to activate from deck Branded Beast. Alternatively, you can activate from deck Branded Lost for further searches/fusion protection.
  6. End phase - set your Branded card of choice from deck. Ideally, you set Branded in Red so you can fusion summon on your opponent's turn. If you already have Branded in Red, you can set Branded Opening for further searches/protection from destruction. 
Branded Fusion + Discard = Red-Eyes Dragoon (Best to use if you suspect your opponent has Nibiru, or you are against a Kashtira player, or if you want to play safe).
  1. Activate Branded Fusion to summon Lubellion the Searing Dragon, sending Albaz + Dark Magician from deck.
  2. Lubellion (discards for cost) fusion summons Dragoon by shuffling back Albaz and Dark Magician from GY to deck.
Cartesia + Light/Dark monster + Either Bystial Saronir/Albion the Shrouded Dragon = Search for any Branded card (Best to use if you're missing a particular Branded card, esp. Branded Fusion!)
  1. Activate Cartesia's effect to fusion summon Granguinol by using Cartesia + Light/Dark monster. If Saronir is in hand, you use Saronir instead.
  2. Granguinol sends to GY from deck Bystial Saronir. (Or Albion the Shrouded Dragon)
  3. Bystial Saronir/Albion the Shrouded Dragon sends to GY Branded Retribution. 
  4. Bystial Saronir/Albion the Shrouded Dragon sends to GY your Branded spell/trap card of choice. 
  5. Banish Branded Retribution from GY to retrieve from GY your Branded spell/trap of choice.
Going first and uninterrupted, your opponent will likely contend with Mirrorjade's banish, a pop with Branded Beast, and a set Branded in Red. Depending on the hand, your opponent may also be dealing with Mercourier's monster negate, Dramaturge's monster negate, Masquerade's -600 burn, and Granguinol can summon Proskenion from the Extra Deck. Red-Eyes Dragoon can also be summoned, a much needed omni-negate that Branded needs. If you're lucky, you also have a facedown Super Polymerization - a devasting turn ending card if used at the right time. Your hand will likely also be sizeable and ready with follow-up for next turn since Cartesia, Alba-Lenatus and Albion generate resources during the end phase.
 
Going second, Branded can slog through interruption, pierce through boards and beat down your opponent's monsters with big beatsticks. Branded is naturally equipped with in-engine ways to play going second. Polymerization fusing into Guardian Chimera is a nigh-unstoppable juggernaut since it's effect is often chainblocked with the fusion material used for it's fusion summon and it is untargetable since you used Polymerization. If Branded Opening is on the field, it also can't be destroyed! Super Polymerization can fuse away most boards in today's meta, especially with Garura, only needing 2 monsters with the same type and attribute. Muddy Mudragon can fuse away your Kashtira opponent's Diablosis + Ariseheart as well! Against the rare Dragon deck, Albaz can contact fuse their problematic Dragons away like Borrload Savage Dragon and Crystal Wing into Alba-Lenatus. Alot of interruption these days involve flipping monsters facedown, destroying and banishing (For example, Traptrix, Labrynth, Ninja and Kashtira does this alot) - Branded is very comfortable with that since they can fuse face down monsters and shuffle back banished monsters with Lubellion to fusion summon.

GENERAL TIPS

  • Try to bait out Ash Blossom by your many searches/summons from deck before you use Branded Fusion. If you don't have Branded Fusion, your opponent will likely hold Ash Blossom in their hand waiting for it, so you can bluff having the card to search/summon all you want!
  • Branded lacks in-engine ways to remove backrow, except with Guardian Chimera. Backrow floodgates absolutely slaughter Branded, so if you're against an opponent using something like Rivalry of Warlords, it probably is time to proceed to next game! Be sure to side in backrow hate in those match-ups!
  •  Guardian Chimera is the best card to crack open established boards. With it's untargetability, beefy 3300ATK/DEF statline and non-targeting destruction, most boards fall to this offensive juggernaut. If your opponent negates Polymerization/Branded in Red to prevent Chimera from coming out, they have wasted a precious interaction paving the way for you to use Branded Fusion.
  • Try to have Cartesia on board before you summon monsters on the field with important effects. Cartesia's quick effect fusion summon allows you to dodge common targeting negates like Impermanence and Effect Veiler.
  • The best cards to side out is the Bystial package, especially when the match-up doesn't call for them (for ex. Traptrix/Kashtira don't have light/dark for Bystials to banish). Super Polymerization can also be sided out in certain matchups where your Super Poly targets don't work out.
  • If Branded Lost is active, Fusion effect's activation cannot be negated. Cards that negate the activation like Baronne De Fleur, Borreload Savage Dragon and even Solemn Judgment cannot negate your Branded Fusion! Branded Lost is a perfect way to bait a negate or to guarantee your Fusion effect when you're against these threats.
  • In certain common meta match-ups, Dragoon is untouchable by your opponent. If you can, try to summon Dragoon before you use key cards like Branded Fusion to guarantee it's resolution. Also, if you want to play around Nibiru, summon Dragoon before 5 summons. Dragoon is also your go-to answer when facing down Kashtira Ariseheart's macro-cosmos like floodgate and targeting banish.
  • Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

CONCLUDING COMMENTARY

The culmination of the "Abyss" storyline also coincides with the strongest form that Branded has ever fielded. All the support for Branded over the last couple years creates a consistent, strong and resilient deck. Naturally playing through established boards while having a robust grind game is only something that few decks can boast. To see for youself how this deck performs vs. meta, I highly recommend you see the deck in action by watching the Youtube video linked below!
 
Our hero, Albaz has faced his enemies to ultimately triumph through trials and adversity. Now, you can do the same thing as you pilot Branded!

GLHF Duelists!

deck_excerpt: Ritual Summon the Legendary Swordsman and wipe out your opponent's board.
deck_description:
- DECK STATS

  • ATTACK: 9/10
  • DEFENSE: 3/10
  • VERSATILITY: 2/10
  • CONSISTENCY: 5/10
  • DIFFICULTY: 3/5
  • OVERALL: 4.75/10
  • TYPE: BOARD BREAKER
  • TIER: FUN / CASUAL

Very satisfying and fun when it works.

 

- HOW TO

A very simple deck to use, but difficult to operate. Its main objective is to clear the opponent's field, either by Spell Cards or using Black Luster Soldier - Legendary Swordsman. However, due to the lack of protection, it is difficult to keep this consistent for many turns, so try to finish as quickly as possible.

Summon monsters like Accesscode Talker and Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder to help you with the board wipe. And if you are in need of protection, your only way is with Black Luster Soldier - Soldier of Chaos summoned with a Level 7+ Monster or Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax summoned using I:P Masquerena.

Your priority is to bring Black Luster Soldier - Legendary Swordsman to the field, keep this in mind. After all, it is your Boss Monster. But sometimes we need to improvise, so don't be afraid to use it as material for Black Luster Soldier - Soldier of Chaos. Besides, Super Soldier Synthesis can summon it back from the GY.

- NOTES AND TIPS

  • Bring forth Black Luster Soldier - Legendary Swordsman and wipe out your opponent's board.
  • If everything goes wrong, Summon Accesscode Talker.
  • Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax is also your friend if everything goes wrong.
  • This deck has quick access to Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder.
  • Number 41: Bagooska the Terribly Tired Tapir and Scareclaw Tri-Heart will buy you time. Always Summon them with priority if you go first.
  • The Battle Phase is where this deck excels, always keep that in mind. Your goal will always be to summon Black Luster Soldier - Legendary Swordsman and go into the Battle Phase.
  • Divine Sword - Phoenix Blade can be used to banish Beginning Knight and Evening Twilight Knight.
  • Always try to use one of the Normal Monsters as material for the Ritual Summon.
  • Keep in mind that this deck is quite limited. Keep an eye on your resources so you don't spend it all in a single turn. However, if the opportunity arises, don't hesitate to finish the duel also in a single turn.

- KEY CARDS

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

.

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

- BASIC COMBO #1 - Going Second

1. Normal Summon Rescue Rabbit and activate its effect.

2. Special Summon 2 x Clavkiys, the Magikey Skyblaster.

3. Special Summon Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights using the two Clavkiys, the Magikey Skyblaster as materials.

4. Add either Noble Knight Artorigus or Envoy of Chaos using Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights' first effect.

5. Activate Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights' second effect and send Divine Sword - Phoenix Blade to the GY. Special Summon Super Soldier Soul.

6. Either Special Summon Linkuriboh using Super Soldier Soul as material or Special Summon a Link Monster using both Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights and Super Soldier Soul.

7. Activate Super Soldier Soul's effect in the GY.

8. Add either Evening Twilight Knight or Beginning Knight to your hand.

- BASIC COMBO #2 - Going First

1. Normal Summon Rescue Rabbit and activate its effect.

2. Special Summon 2 x Clavkiys, the Magikey Skyblaster.

3. Special Summon Number 41: Bagooska the Terribly Tired Tapir using the two Clavkiys, the Magikey Skyblaster as materials.

- BASIC COMBO #3 - Going First or Second

1. Activate Unexpected Dai and Special Summon Noble Knight Artorigus.

2. Normal Summon Rescue Rabbit and activate its effect.

3. Special Summon 2 x Clavkiys, the Magikey Skyblaster.

4. Special Summon Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights using the two Clavkiys, the Magikey Skyblaster as materials.

5. Add Black Luster Soldier - Envoy of the Beginning using Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights' first effect.

6. Activate Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights' second effect and send Divine Sword - Phoenix Blade to the GY. Special Summon Super Soldier Soul.

7. Special Summon I:P Masquerena using Super Soldier Soul and Noble Knight Artorigus.

8. Special Summon Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax using Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights and I:P Masquerena.

- ADVANCED COMBO

1. Normal Summon Rescue Rabbit and activate its effect.

2. Special Summon 2 x Clavkiys, the Magikey Skyblaster.

3. Special Summon Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights using the two Clavkiys, the Magikey Skyblaster as materials.

4. Add Noble Knight Artorigus using Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights' first effect.

5. Activate Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights' second effect and send Divine Sword - Phoenix Blade to the GY. Special Summon Super Soldier Soul.

6. Either Special Summon Linkuriboh using Super Soldier Soul as material or Special Summon a Link Monster using both Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights and Super Soldier Soul.

7. Activate Super Soldier Soul's effect in the GY.

8. Add Beginning Knight to your hand.

9. Activate Super Soldier Synthesis and Special Summon Black Luster Soldier - Legendary Swordsman using Evening Twilight Knight (Deck) and Beginning Knight (Hand),

10. Special Summon Black Luster Soldier - Envoy of the Beginning banishing Evening Twilight and Beginning.

11. Activate their effects and add another Black Luster Soldier - Legendary Swordsman and Super Soldier Ritual.

12. Special Summon your second Black Luster Soldier - Legendary Swordsman using Noble Knight Artorigus and Beginning Knight.

Note: Your opening hand must be Black Luster Soldier - Envoy of the Beginning, Black Luster Soldier - Legendary Swordsman, Super Soldier Synthesis, Beginning Knight and Rescue Rabbit.

deck_excerpt: Level 5/7 and occasionally 8 Synchros alongside Triamid Field Spell loop to Triamid Sphinx.
deck_description:
This deck is more Triamid than Adamancipator. Only play this deck if you enjoy Triamid and would like to use them.

Use Ancient Fairy Dragon to give you access to Triamid Hunter through Triamid Cruiser if you draw Adamancipator Analyzer or Doki Doki.

Garden Rose Flora has synergy with Triamid Field spells, triggering their effects when sent to the graveyard. This can search with Triamid Cruiser when you otherwise cannot get it into the graveyard. You can then go into a Level 7 Synchro with the Token summoned by Flora.

Ideally, your Level 5 Synchro will be Naturia Beast, if you hard drew into your Field Spells and do not need to use Garden Rose Flora.

Triamid Pulse is an extremely valuable trap. Use it to destroy your opponents face-up cards, as well as special summon needed Adamancipator or Triamid monsters from the Graveyard.
